{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4eeb37e3-5cea-46cb-8630-2d56316e921c","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01RLXX7s4YYQUFXBbT6Q8L9b","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Answering .NET DSA question"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01SJLTXZYwRPsSoG1x92Psyz","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-30eef095a5f245d48ff694450b138250"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-30eef095a5f245d48ff694450b138250."}],"interactionId":"ee21a07a-cd54-4084-be7a-c586b126b750","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for older/weaker cryptographic algorithms. Specifically, DSA (the original DSA, not ECDSA) has been deprecated and removed on certain platforms.\n\nLet me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7, Microsoft made DSA operations throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS (and iOS/tvOS). This is because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. The .NET runtime on macOS relied on Apple's native crypto libraries for DSA, and when Apple removed DSA support, .NET couldn't provide it anymore.\n \nBut wait, the user says their code works on .NET 10 but breaks on .NET 11. That's strange given that the DSA removal on macOS happened back in .NET 7. Let me check the timeline here—if it broke in .NET 7, it should have already been broken in .NET 10. Unless there's something else going on, or maybe I'm misremembering when this change was introduced. I'm reconsidering the timeline here—if the user says it works on .NET 10 but fails on .NET 11, then maybe the breaking change happened between those versions rather than in .NET 7. It's possible DSA was marked obsolete in .NET 7 with warnings, but the actual runtime exception on macOS came later, perhaps in .NET 11 when Apple's security framework changes finally forced the issue.\n\nThe core problem is that macOS dropped DSA support in its native cryptographic libraries, so .NET can't provide it either. The main workarounds are using a third-party library like BouncyCastle, switching to OpenSSL through P/Invoke, migrating away from DSA if only signature verification is needed, or using conditional compilation to handle macOS differently.\n\nI should check if there's relevant code in the current directory before giving a final answer, since this might be a practical implementation question rather than just theoretical.","outputTokens":1150,"requestId":"D820:11463F:62D943B:6C112AC:69F1630F"},"id":"338ecd8a-ee8f-4ca9-b336-17b0a250ce98","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:21.955Z","parentId":"29dc5ffa-0f20-47b3-873a-738470cb5a7d"}
