{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b584b9a1-694b-457e-835b-a2af5a645403","content":"## What happened\n\nApple removed DSA from its native Security framework. .NET on macOS delegates to the platform crypto libraries, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**. On Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG), DSA is still available, which is why only macOS breaks.\n\nThe API was already marked obsolete (`SYSLIB0039`) in earlier releases; .NET 11 completes the removal on macOS.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification)**\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Import your existing DSA public key (e.g., from X.509 SubjectPublicKeyInfo)\nvar publicKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(spkiBytes);\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nThis is a fully managed implementation — no platform dependency.\n\n**Option 2 — Runtime platform check with conditional fallback**\n\nIf you want to keep `System.Security.Cryptography.DSA` on platforms that support it and fall back only on macOS:\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // ... existing verification code\n}\nelse\n{\n    // BouncyCastle fallback (as above)\n}\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Migrate away from DSA entirely**\n\nIf you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, which are supported everywhere. DSA is considered legacy and is ≤1024-bit in many implementations.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR**: Apple dropped DSA → .NET 11 on macOS can't provide it → use BouncyCastle for a portable managed implementation, or migrate to ECDSA/RSA.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee21a07a-cd54-4084-be7a-c586b126b750","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a pure knowledge question. Let me answer based on what I know.\n\nThe key issue: Apple removed DSA support from its native cryptographic frameworks. .NET on macOS uses the platform's native crypto (Apple Security framework / CryptoKit). When Apple dropped DSA, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nThis was originally introduced as a breaking change in .NET 7 (with obsoletion SYSLIB0039). But the user says it works in .NET 10 and breaks in .NET 11. It's possible that:\n- In earlier versions, there was still some path that worked\n\n\n- Or in .NET 11, a previously-suppressed exception is now thrown\n- Or the managed fallback was removed\n\nRegardless, the fundamental cause and fix remain the same. Let me give a clear answer.","outputTokens":751,"requestId":"D820:11463F:62DE440:6C1712C:69F16329"},"id":"8fe543f1-4b05-47e9-9c40-80ea32ce5662","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:39.530Z","parentId":"b401e302-bd25-4a6b-a023-3f05c35ab37e"}
